# Zed Lite Agent Rules

`AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and `GEMINI.md` are symlinks to this file. Keep this
file focused on rules that matter for this lite fork.

## Product Scope

- The product name is **Zed Lite**.
- There is only one product/channel identity: `lite`.
- Do not reintroduce dev, nightly, preview, stable, or any other channel split.
- Keep the bundle identifier/app id as `dev.zed-lite.Zed` unless explicitly
  asked to rename the product.
- Preserve the lite scope: local editor, Git/Git UI, terminal, settings,
  language/theme extensions, LSP, diagnostics, search, and Markdown/CSV/SVG/image
  previews.
- Removed areas stay removed unless explicitly requested: AI, agents, edit
  prediction, model providers, web search, login, cloud API, collaboration,
  calls, channels, remote development, WSL/dev containers, debugger/DAP, REPL,
  notebooks, onboarding, auto-update, and multi-channel release automation.

## Build and Packaging

- Use lite builds by default:

```sh
cargo check -p zed --no-default-features --features zed/lite
cargo build -p zed --no-default-features --features zed/lite
```

- When building app and CLI together, use:

```sh
cargo build --no-default-features --features zed/lite,cli/lite --package zed --package cli
```

- Packaging scripts must build only Zed Lite:
  - `script/bundle-linux`
  - `script/bundle-mac`
  - `script/bundle-windows.ps1`
- GitHub packaging is `.github/workflows/build_lite.yml`.
- Pushes to `main` build all platform artifacts and upload them to the Actions
  run only; they do not publish a GitHub Release.
- Publishing a release requires a `v*` tag, for example:

```sh
git tag v0.1.0
git push origin v0.1.0
```

- The release job must depend on all platform bundle jobs, download their
  artifacts, then create/update the matching GitHub Release and upload assets.
  Keep `actions/checkout` in the release job and pass `--repo
  "${GITHUB_REPOSITORY}"` to `gh release` commands so the job does not depend on
  implicit local git state.
- Rerunning a `main` workflow run will not publish a release because the release
  job is intentionally skipped outside `v*` tags. To retry a failed release,
  rerun the tag workflow or move/push the tag to a fixed commit.
- Do not add release workflows that distinguish dev/nightly/preview/stable.
- macOS CI may ad-hoc sign when Apple notarization secrets are absent. That is
  acceptable for artifacts unless real notarized distribution is explicitly in
  scope.

## Rust Coding Guidelines

- Prioritize correctness and clarity. Speed is secondary unless requested.
- Prefer existing files and existing local patterns over new abstractions.
- Avoid creating many small files.
- Do not add `mod.rs`; use named module files instead.
- When creating a new crate, specify `[lib] path = "...rs"` when appropriate.
- Avoid `unwrap()` and indexing that can panic. Propagate errors with `?` when
  the caller can handle them.
- Never silently discard fallible errors with `let _ =`. Propagate, handle, or
  log with `.log_err()` or equivalent.
- Async failures should reach the UI layer when they affect the user.
- Use full-word variable names.
- Use variable shadowing to narrow clone lifetimes in async code:

```rust
executor.spawn({
    let task_ran = task_ran.clone();
    async move {
        *task_ran.borrow_mut() = true;
    }
});
```

## GPUI Rules

- Context arguments are named `cx`.
- Window arguments are named `window` and come before `cx`.
- Inside `Entity::update`, `update_in`, listeners, and subscriptions, use the
  inner `cx`, not an outer captured `cx`.
- Avoid updating an entity while it is already being updated.
- Store, await, or detach tasks. Dropping a `Task` cancels it.
- Call `cx.notify()` when state changes affect rendering.
- Use `cx.listener` for event handlers that mutate the current entity.
- Use `WeakEntity` where cyclic ownership could leak.

## Tests

- In GPUI tests, prefer GPUI executor timers:

```rust
cx.background_executor().timer(duration).await
```

- Avoid `smol::Timer::after(...)` in tests that rely on `run_until_parked()`.
- Keep test coverage proportional to risk. Broaden it when changing shared
  behavior or user workflows.

## Editing Rules

- Use `rg` for code search.
- Use `apply_patch` for manual edits.
- Do not use destructive git commands unless explicitly requested.
- Do not revert user changes. Work with the current tree.
- Keep comments sparse. Explain non-obvious why, not what the code says.
- Default to ASCII for new text unless the surrounding file already uses
  non-ASCII or the content requires it.

## Pull Request Hygiene

- Use a clear imperative PR title.
- Do not use conventional commit prefixes in PR titles.
- Include `Release Notes:` as the final PR body section.
- Use exactly one bullet under `Release Notes:`.
- For docs-only or internal-only changes:

```md
Release Notes:

- N/A
```

## Rules Hygiene

- Keep `.rules` high-signal.
- Add new rules only when they are non-obvious, repeatedly encountered, and
  specific enough to act on.
- Do not add architectural maps that will go stale.
- Prefer crate-local rules for crate-specific traps.
